data.content:
Yes — use the generic `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>`, which asserts the type **and** returns the typed instance:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

This eliminates the hard cast and gives a clear failure message (e.g., "Expected type: EmailHandler. Actual type: SmsHandler.") instead of an `InvalidCastException`. The generic overload (MSTest v3+) returns the cast object so you can continue asserting on it.
